---
import ClosingCostCalculator from '@/components/sections/closing-cost-calculator';
import LendCityCtaBanner from '@/components/sections/lendcity-cta-banner';
import ShareResults from '@/components/sections/share-results';
import DefaultLayout from '@/layouts/DefaultLayout.astro';
---

<DefaultLayout
  title="Closing Cost Calculator — FirstHomeGuide.ca"
  description="Estimate your total closing costs including legal fees, land transfer tax, PST on CMHC insurance, and more. Province-specific calculations for Canadian first-time home buyers."
>
  <section class="pt-8 md:pt-12 lg:pt-16 pb-0">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl">
      <a
        href="/tools"
        class="text-muted-foreground hover:text-foreground mb-2 inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-sm transition-colors"
      >
        &larr; All Tools
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="tool-subpage">
    <ClosingCostCalculator client:load />
  </div>

  <section class="pb-4 pt-0">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl flex justify-end">
      <ShareResults
        client:load
        title="Closing Cost Calculator Results"
        summary="Estimate closing costs including legal fees, land transfer tax, and total cash needed — FirstHomeGuide.ca"
        toolUrl="/tools/closing-cost-calculator"
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-padding pt-8 pb-0">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl">
      <div class="prose prose-neutral dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
        <h2>What Are Closing Costs in Canada?</h2>
        <p>Closing costs are the fees and expenses you pay on top of your down payment when you finalize a home purchase. In Canada, they typically range from 1.5% to 4% of the purchase price. On a $500,000 home, that means $7,500 to $20,000 in additional cash you need to have ready on closing day. These costs are not optional, and most of them cannot be rolled into your mortgage. First-time buyers are often caught off guard by these expenses, so budgeting for them early is essential.</p>

        <h3>Land Transfer Tax</h3>
        <p>Land transfer tax is usually the single largest closing cost. Every province except Alberta and Saskatchewan charges a tax when property changes hands, and rates vary significantly. In <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/document/land-transfer-tax" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">Ontario</a>, the tax is tiered: 0.5% on the first $55,000, 1% on $55,001 to $250,000, 1.5% on $250,001 to $400,000, and 2% on $400,001 to $2,000,000. On a $500,000 home in Ontario, you would pay approximately $6,475. Toronto buyers face an additional municipal land transfer tax at matching rates, effectively doubling the bill. In <a href="https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/taxes/property-taxes/property-transfer-tax" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">British Columbia</a>, the property transfer tax runs from 1% on the first $200,000 up to 5% on amounts over $3,000,000. Alberta charges only a modest registration fee of roughly $400.</p>

        <h3>Legal Fees and Title Insurance</h3>
        <p>You are required to have a real estate lawyer (or notary in BC and Quebec) handle the closing of your purchase. Legal fees typically range from $1,500 to $2,500 and cover the review of your purchase agreement, title search, mortgage registration, and the transfer of funds. Title insurance is a one-time premium of $250 to $500 that protects you and your lender against title defects, fraud, and encroachment issues. Most lenders require title insurance as a condition of funding your mortgage.</p>

        <h3>Other Common Closing Costs</h3>
        <p>Beyond the major items, several smaller costs add up quickly. A home inspection costs $400 to $600 and is strongly recommended even though it is not legally required. An appraisal, if your lender orders one, runs $300 to $500. Property tax adjustments reimburse the seller for any taxes they have prepaid beyond the closing date. Utility adjustments work the same way for water and sewer charges. Moving costs, immediate repairs, and utility hookup fees should also be part of your budget.</p>

        <h3>First-Time Buyer Rebates</h3>
        <p>Most provinces offer land transfer tax relief for first-time buyers. In Ontario, you can receive a rebate of up to $4,000 on the provincial land transfer tax, which fully covers the tax on homes up to $368,000. In Toronto, first-time buyers also receive an additional rebate of up to $4,475 on the municipal land transfer tax. In <a href="https://www2.gov.bc.ca/gov/content/taxes/property-taxes/property-transfer-tax" target="_blank" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer">British Columbia</a>, first-time buyers are fully exempt from the property transfer tax on homes priced at $500,000 or less, with a partial exemption on homes up to $835,000. Check your province's specific program to confirm eligibility.</p>

        <h3>How much cash do I need at closing?</h3>
        <p>Plan for your down payment plus 1.5% to 4% of the purchase price in closing costs. On a $500,000 home with 5% down, budget approximately $25,000 for the down payment plus $15,000 to $20,000 for closing costs — a total of $40,000 to $45,000 in cash. Some costs like the home inspection and appraisal are paid before closing, so you will need that money available even earlier.</p>

        <h3>Is land transfer tax included in my mortgage?</h3>
        <p>No. Land transfer tax must be paid from your own funds at closing and cannot be added to your mortgage. This is a cash expense that comes directly out of your savings, which is why it surprises so many buyers. The only exception is in some provinces where first-time buyer rebates effectively eliminate or reduce the tax. Always confirm the exact amount with your real estate lawyer before closing day.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-padding pt-0">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl">
      <LendCityCtaBanner
        client:visible
        headline="No surprises at closing"
        description="Our concierge team walks you through every cost and coordinates your entire closing process — book a free call to get started."
      />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section-padding pt-8">
    <div class="container max-w-screen-xl">
      <h2 class="mb-3 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight">Learn more</h2>
      <ul class="text-muted-foreground space-y-2 text-sm leading-relaxed">
        <li>Read our <a href="/guide/7-closing-the-deal/1-closing-costs-overview/" class="text-foreground underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-chart-1">closing costs overview</a> to understand why these costs surprise so many first-time buyers.</li>
        <li>See a <a href="/guide/7-closing-the-deal/2-cost-breakdown/" class="text-foreground underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-chart-1">detailed cost breakdown</a> of every fee you should plan for, from legal fees to utility adjustments.</li>
        <li>Learn how <a href="/guide/7-closing-the-deal/3-land-transfer-tax/" class="text-foreground underline underline-offset-4 hover:text-chart-1">land transfer tax</a> is calculated in your province — usually your single largest closing cost.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</DefaultLayout>
